    "ShortQuestions": [
        {
            "id": 1,
            "question": "Explain the difference between 'break' and 'continue' with an example.",
            "preferredAnswer": "Break terminates the loop completely. Execution moves to the first line after the loop.\nContinue skips only the current iteration and jumps back to the top of the loop to start the next cycle.\n\nExample:\nfor i in range(5):\n    if i == 2: continue  # Skips printing 2\n    if i == 4: break     # Stops the loop entirely before printing 4\n    print(i)\nOutput: 0, 1, 3"
        },
        {
            "id": 2,
            "question": "Why does range(5) produce numbers 0 to 4 instead of 1 to 5?",
            "preferredAnswer": "Python uses zero-based indexing. The range(start, stop) function includes the start value but excludes the stop value. range(5) defaults start to 0. So it counts 0, 1, 2, 3, 4. This is extremely convenient because it runs exactly 5 times, matching the argument provided."
        },
        {
            "id": 3,
            "question": "Write a while loop that prints numbers from 1 to 5.",
            "preferredAnswer": "count = 1\nwhile count <= 5:\n    print(count)\n    count += 1\n\nKey points: Initialize the variable before the loop, check the condition, and remember to increment the variable inside the loop to avoid an infinite loop."
        },
        {
            "id": 4,
            "question": "What is the important difference between using 'elif' and multiple separate 'if' statements?",
            "preferredAnswer": "'elif' creates an exclusive chain: only the first matching block will run, and all later conditions are ignored.\n\nIf you used multiple 'if' statements instead of 'elif', Python would check every single one, potentially executing multiple blocks of code if conditions overlap. Use elif when you want exactly one outcome."
        },
